5:42 I tend to agree with Mourinho, but he should stick to calling it VA ;-)
It was one of our poorer performances overall and we looked tired at the end. Could have rued some huge missed chances, but, fortunately, Spurs' finishing wasn't sexy either. The sting of 97 points not being enough is good fuel and motivation, so keep taking it 1 match at a time, fully focused on the wins-only approach, Redmen! YNWA

snippet.textDisplay: Any team who wants to beat liverpool has to take every chance they get and hope liverpool aren't clinical themselves. Spurs did okay defensively and got lucky with liverpool missing many chances, but they couldn't score and lost because of that. Barcelona and Messi almost beat them last year; they punished liverpool for being wasteful and could have been 4 or 5 nil up in the first leg, but only got to 3 and bottled it in the second leg because they couldn't defend and didn't finish off the chances that Messi created. Napoli did beat them this year over two legs, by being clinical up front and strong defensively (a lot of tactical fouls, mostly on liverpool's full backs). That is what Atletico have to do in February.

snippet.textDisplay: It is easy to forget, that even though Liverpool grind results game after game, these opponents like Tottenham today are top of the top of cream in football, as are all EPL teams. Only in Europe there are thousands of clubs that play football more or less seriously, same amount in Latin America, Africa and Asia, and these players who make it to EPL squad playing most of the games are aberrations in nature. So there are going to be moments, when Liverpool are under pressure, maybe even losing (or then not...) or in trouble in a game, it is just impossible to clear everything and everyone out of the way just like that. Tottenham caused us trouble for 20 minutes. I´d be worried if they didn´t! Highest possible level in a sport that is the biggest on Earth... No one will just dominate every game all the time. Three points, is it the ManUrine´s next...
